"# Chapter 2 — Logic gates and adders

Transistors are switches. Arrange them in small groups and you get
logic gates. Arrange gates and you get adders. Arrange adders and you
get processors. The whole tower.

## The gates

A logic gate takes one or two Boolean inputs — TRUE or FALSE, 1 or
0, high voltage or low voltage — and produces a Boolean output.
There are six basic gates that every chip on Earth is built from:

- **NOT** (inverter): one input, one output. Output is the opposite.
- **AND**: two inputs. Output is TRUE only if both inputs are TRUE.
- **OR**: two inputs. Output is TRUE if either input is TRUE.
- **NAND**: AND followed by NOT.
- **NOR**: OR followed by NOT.
- **XOR** (exclusive-or): TRUE if the inputs differ.

That's it. Six gates. Every processor ever made is arrangements of
these six ideas, plus some memory cells (which are themselves
arrangements of these gates).

You can make them all from NAND alone. This is called functional
completeness. NAND is a universal gate. Give me NAND, I'll build you
NOT (NAND with both inputs tied together), AND (NAND followed by
NOT), OR (NOTs feeding into a NAND), and so on. So in principle a
chip could be built from a single kind of gate.

In practice chips use several kinds because it's more efficient. But
the theoretical fact — one gate is enough — is worth carrying.

## Motoi Scheme as gates

Motoi Scheme has these built in. They live under the names `and`,
`or`, `not`. Let's show them:

```
(and #t #t)  ;; => #t
(and #t #f)  ;; => #f
(or #f #t)   ;; => #t
(or #f #f)   ;; => #f
(not #t)     ;; => #f
```

Boolean logic. Same shape as the gates in silicon, just in software.

We can build a half-adder in Motoi Scheme. A half-adder adds two
one-bit numbers and produces two outputs: a sum and a carry:

```
(define (half-adder a b)
  (let ((sum   (xor a b))
        (carry (and a b)))
    (list sum carry)))

(define (xor a b)
  (and (or a b) (not (and a b))))

(half-adder #f #f)  ;; => (#f #f)  ;; 0 + 0 = 0, carry 0
(half-adder #f #t)  ;; => (#t #f)  ;; 0 + 1 = 1, carry 0
(half-adder #t #f)  ;; => (#t #f)  ;; 1 + 0 = 1, carry 0
(half-adder #t #t)  ;; => (#f #t)  ;; 1 + 1 = 0, carry 1  (that's binary two)
```

A full adder adds three bits — two inputs plus an incoming carry —
and produces a sum and an outgoing carry. Chain full adders together
and you can add two multi-bit numbers.

```
(define (full-adder a b cin)
  (let* ((h1 (half-adder a b))
         (s1 (car h1))
         (c1 (cadr h1))
         (h2 (half-adder s1 cin))
         (s2 (car h2))
         (c2 (cadr h2))
         (cout (or c1 c2)))
    (list s2 cout)))

(full-adder #t #t #f)  ;; 1 + 1 + 0 = 2, so sum=0, carry=1
;; => (#f #t)

(full-adder #t #t #t)  ;; 1 + 1 + 1 = 3, so sum=1, carry=1
;; => (#t #t)
```

Now chain full-adders together to build an 8-bit adder. In real
silicon this is called a ripple-carry adder, and it lives at the
heart of every processor's ALU (arithmetic-logic unit).

```
(define (bits n width)
  ;; convert integer n to list of #t/#f, low bit first
  (if (= width 0)
      '()
      (cons (odd? n) (bits (quotient n 2) (- width 1)))))

(define (bits->int lst)
  (let loop ((bs lst) (place 1) (total 0))
    (if (null? bs)
        total
        (loop (cdr bs)
              (* place 2)
              (+ total (if (car bs) place 0))))))

(define (ripple-add a-bits b-bits)
  (let loop ((a a-bits) (b b-bits) (cin #f) (out '()))
    (if (null? a)
        (reverse (cons cin out))
        (let* ((r (full-adder (car a) (car b) cin))
               (s (car r))
               (c (cadr r)))
          (loop (cdr a) (cdr b) c (cons s out))))))

;; Add 42 + 17 as 8-bit numbers
(let* ((a (bits 42 8))
       (b (bits 17 8))
       (sum (ripple-add a b)))
  (bits->int sum))
;; => 59
```

That's an adder, built out of pure Boolean logic, in Motoi Scheme.
The identical shape — same gates, same connections — is what lives
inside every chip's ALU. In silicon each gate is a few transistors;
in Motoi Scheme each gate is a Scheme procedure. Same logic, different
substrate.

## ENIAC

The first American general-purpose electronic computer, ENIAC, was
completed in 1945 at the University of Pennsylvania. It contained
about 17,468 vacuum tubes (not transistors — transistors weren't
invented yet). It filled a room. It could perform about 5,000 add
operations per second.

A modern smartphone processor performs on the order of a hundred
billion add operations per second. Every one of them is the same
half-adder / full-adder shape.

The gates got smaller. The idea stayed the same.

## What Motoi wants you to take from this

Computation is arrangement. You take a small handful of simple
pieces — six kinds of logic gate — and combine them in the right
shapes and you get everything a computer can do. The pieces are
simple. The arrangements can be enormous.

When Motoi tells you that programming is composition, this is what
he means at the bottom. Composition all the way down.")
